tmatter><trail><crumb>3</crumb></trail> <anchor>15151</anchor> <rss>jms-009V.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Project</taxon> <addr>jms-009V</addr>  <route>jms-009V.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year>  </date> <authors><author><link href="foscoloregian.xml" type="local">Fosco Loregian</link></author><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author><author><link href="danielepalombi.xml" type="local">Daniele Palombi</link></author> </authors> <title>Higher duploid theory</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A project to explore the category theory of <link href="munch-2014.xml" type="local" title="Models of a non-associative composition">duploids</link> and their higher-dimensional generalizations.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15152</anchor> <rss>jonmsterling.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Person</taxon> <addr>jonmsterling</addr>  <route>jonmsterling.xml</route>   <title>Jon Sterling</title> <meta name="external">https://www.jonmsterling.com/</meta><meta name="institution"><link href="ucam.xml" type="local" title="University of Cambridge">University of Cambridge</link></meta><meta name="orcid">0000-0002-0585-5564</meta><meta name="position">Associate Professor</meta><meta name="phd-advisor">robertharper</meta><meta name="postdoc-advisor">larsbirkedal</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Associate Professor in Logical Foundations and Formal Methods at University of Cambridge. Formerly a <link href="jms-0061.xml" type="local" title="TypeSynth: synthetic methods in program verification">Marie Skłodowska-Curie Postdoctoral Fellow</link> hosted at Aarhus University by <link href="larsbirkedal.xml" type="local" title="Lars Birkedal">Lars Birkedal</link>, and before this a PhD student of <link href="robertharper.xml" type="local" title="Robert Harper">Robert Harper</link>.</p>              
            
          
          </mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>15153</anchor> <rss>munch-2014.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>munch-2014</addr>  <route>munch-2014.xml</route>  <authors><author><link href="guillaumemunch.xml" type="local">Guillaume Munch-Maccagnoni</link></author> </authors> <title>Models of a non-associative composition</title> <meta name="doi">10.1007/978-3-642-54830-7_26</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We characterise the polarised evaluation order through a categorical structure where the hypothesis that composition is associative is relaxed. Duploid is the name of the structure, as a reference to Jean-Louis Loday’s duplicial algebras. The main result is a reflection <tex>\textit{Adj} \to \textit{Dupl}</tex> where <tex>\textit{Dupl}</tex> is a category of duploids and duploid functors, and <tex>\textit{Adj}</tex> is the category of adjunctions and pseudo maps of adjunctions. The result suggests that the various biases in denotational semantics: indirect, call-by-value, call-by-name… are a way of hiding the fact that composition is not always associative.</p></mainmatter> </tree></references></backmatter></tree>